  <!-- ============ FAQ ============ -->
  <section class="faq-band" id="faq">
    <svg class="botan faq-botan" viewBox="0 0 200 200" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
      <g>
        <path d="M185 25 C165 60 140 88 112 108" stroke="#5E6B4F" stroke-width="1.8" fill="none" opacity="0.55"/>
        <ellipse cx="150" cy="62" rx="10" ry="16" fill="#5E6B4F" opacity="0.35" transform="rotate(30 150 62)"/>
        <ellipse cx="98" cy="118" rx="28" ry="34" fill="#D99FB0" opacity="0.5"/>
        <path d="M98 86 C111 94 117 108 113 122 C109 134 100 142 98 144 C96 142 87 134 83 122 C79 108 85 94 98 86Z" fill="#C77D7D" opacity="0.45"/>
        <circle cx="98" cy="118" r="9" fill="#E8C46A" opacity="0.75"/>
      </g>
    </svg>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="section-head reveal">
        <p class="eyebrow">Good Questions</p>
        <h2>Before you decide</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list reveal">
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Is frozen really as good as fresh?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer"><p>It's the same food from the same kitchen. Every dish is cooked fresh in our own Walnut, CA kitchen, then frozen to hold its nourishment until it reaches you. Thaw it in the refrigerator, heat it through, and it tastes the way it was cooked — warm and home-style, nothing like a supermarket TV dinner. Frozen is simply how we bring a real Zuo Yue Zi to families who live far from fresh delivery.</p></div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>What's the difference between Frozen Herbal and Frozen Classic?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Think of them as two halves of the same tradition. Both plans bring the same full menu from the same kitchen — the meals, the desserts, the Taiwanese postpartum soups — the food that does the rebuilding, staged to your recovery.</p>
            <p>The Frozen Herbal adds the other half: the 30-day herbal drinks, included. These aren't one drink repeated — they're a sequence of 15 formulas that changes as your body moves through the weeks, the inner side of Zuo Yue Zi that food alone doesn't reach, already brewed and packed with your meals so you never have to think about it.</p>
            <p>So the real question isn't the price — it's how much you want handled for you. Choose <em>Frozen Herbal</em> to have the whole tradition taken care of; choose <em>Frozen Classic</em> if you'd rather have the meals now and add the herbal drinks by the week at {usd(products.frozen_herbal_drink_7_1w.price)}/week, or take the standalone <em>Herbal Pack</em> for {usd(products.herbal_drink_pack_30d.price)}.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Will a month of frozen food fit in my freezer?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer"><p>Longer plans ship weekly, so you're only ever storing about a week at a time. Many families keep five days in the freezer and let a couple of days thaw in the refrigerator. If space is truly tight, a small upright freezer is often enough — and it earns its keep long after the confinement month.</p></div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>How do I reheat the meals?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer"><p>Thaw overnight in the refrigerator, then reheat until it's piping hot all the way through — an internal temperature of 165&deg;F (74&deg;C) is the safe mark for reheated food. Each day arrives pre-portioned in its own pillow-size thermal bag, so there's no meal planning, no labels to decode, and nothing to assemble — grab one bag, that's your day.</p></div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>What if I'm not breastfeeding?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer"><p>We'll remove the milk-stimulating ingredients from your menu. The food still does its main job — restoring blood, warmth, and energy after birth. One honest note: fewer ingredients means fewer dishes in rotation, so the menu can feel slightly more repetitive.</p></div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>When should I order?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer"><p>At least one month before your due date, if you can. The week your baby arrives, you will not have the bandwidth to compare plans or fill out forms — and you shouldn't have to. Your shipments start when you tell us the baby has arrived, not on a fixed calendar.</p></div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

